\begin_layout Title
Linearizing deformations of the harmonic source-filter model with the spiral
 scattering transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Vincent Lostanlen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
A classical model for voiced speech production consists in the convolution
 of a harmonic glottal source 
\begin_inset Formula $e(t)$
\end_inset

 with a vocal tract filter 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Introducing indepedent deformations to both components brings realistic
 variability to pitch and spectral envelope.
 We study the decomposition of the deformed source-filter model in the spiral
 scattering transform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Deformations of the harmonic comb
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

-periodic Dirac pulse train is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e(t)=2\pi\sum_{n=-\infty}^{+\infty}\delta(t-2\pi n).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Poisson summation formula states that the Fourier transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $e(t)$
\end_inset

 is a Dirac pulse train of fundamental frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{e}(\omega)=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}e(t)\exp(-\mathrm{i}\omega t)\,\mathrm{d}\omega=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{+\infty}\exp(\mathrm{i}k\omega).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\mathcal{C}^{3}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 a time warp function whose first derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}(t)$
\end_inset

 is positive for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We defined a warped source as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{\theta}(t)=(e\circ\theta)(t)=2\pi\sum_{n=-\infty}^{+\infty}\delta(\theta(t)-2\pi n).
\]

\end_inset

Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the fundamental frequency of 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\theta}(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Deformations of the broadband filter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)$
\end_inset

 be the impulse response of a broadband filter.
 Its Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 is the spectral envelope, and is related to the properties of the vocal
 tract in speech production.
 Again, we define a time warp funtion 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\in\mathcal{C}^{3}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\nu}(t)>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Its derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\nu}(t)$
\end_inset

 is a local dilation factor for the spectral envelope 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}(\omega)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Deformed source-filter model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We extend the classical source filter model 
\begin_inset Formula $[e\ast h](t)$
\end_inset

 by warping independently the source and the filter before combining them:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(t)=[e_{\theta}\ast h_{\nu}](t).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Main result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will show that, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\nu}(t)$
\end_inset

 reasonably regular over the support of first-order wavelets 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)$
\end_inset

, the local maxima of spiral scattering coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(t,\log\lambda_{1},\log\lambda_{2})$
\end_inset

 are clustered on a plane in the 
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha,\beta,\gamma)$
\end_inset

 space of scattering frequencies, where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 is the frequency along time, in Hertz.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quefrency
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 along chromas, in cycles per octaves.
 Typically, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert\beta\vert\geq1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quefrency
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 across octaves, in cycles per octaves.
 Typically, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert\gamma\vert\le1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This plane satisfies the Cartesian equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha+\dfrac{\ddot{\theta}(t)}{\dot{\theta}(t)}\beta+\dfrac{\ddot{\nu}(t)}{\dot{\nu}(t)}\gamma=0.
\]

\end_inset

This result means that harmonic sounds overlapping both in time and frequency
 could be resolved according to their respective source-filter velocities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Outline of the proof
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our proof is organized as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Assuming that the spectral envelope is almost constant over the frequential
 support of the wavelet, the convolution between 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}$
\end_inset

 can be factorized as a product between the Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}$
\end_inset

, up to a phase shift.
\begin_inset Foot
