 formulation
\emph on
 
\emph default
of the wavelet ridge theorem.
 Whereas the wavelet ridge theorem assumes that the signal has slowly varying
 amplitude and fundamental frequency over the support of the wavelet, here
 we assume that the wavelet has slowly varying amplitude over the support
 of the signal.
 Henceforth, the roles of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

analytic signal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

analytic wavelet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are interchanged.
 The form of the result remains the same.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 lowest partials in the harmonic comb do not interfere.
 Thus, we may apply the wavelet ridge theorem to each of them independently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Combining the two previous results yields a factorization of deformed source
 and deformed filter in the scalogram.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The harmonicity property implies that the convolution along chromas only
 applies to the deformed source.
 In turn, the spectral smoothness property implies that the convolution
 across octaves only applies to the deformed filter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We use the wavelet ridge theorem to give the phase of the deformed source
 after convolution along chromas.
 The same theorem applies to the deformed filter after convolution across
 octaves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The two phase functions extracted in the previous part add up.
 Hence, after convolution along chromas and across octaves, the analytic
 amplitude and instantaneous frequency along time are available in closed
 form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We use the wavelet ridge theorem a third time to localize in time the relative
 variations of the two instantaneous frequencies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Cartesian equation is derived from the extraction of spiral wavelet
 ridges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We work under the following assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 large enough to discriminate non-negligible partials,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
slowly varying source: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\ddot{\theta}/\dot{\theta}\Vert_{\infty}\ll\lambda_{1}/Q$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
slowly varying filter: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\ddot{\nu}/\dot{\nu}\Vert_{\infty}\ll\lambda_{1}/Q$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
spectral envelope is almost constant over one semitone: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\dot{\hat{h}}/\hat{h}\Vert_{\infty}\ll Q/\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
spectral envelope is almost linear over one octave.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, we use the fact that harmonicity implies self-similarity: 
\begin_inset Formula $e(t)=e(2^{n}t)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert t\vert>2\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 By means of the Poisson summation formula, this rewrites in the Fourier
 domain as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{e}(\omega)=\hat{e}(2^{j}\omega)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert\omega\vert>1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Wavelet filter bank
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 be a real symmetric window of bandwidth 
\begin_inset Formula $1/Q$
\end_inset

 and unit norm.
 An approximately analytic wavelet is constructed by multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 with a sine wave of frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(t)=g(t)\exp(\mathrm{i}t).
\]

\end_inset

Dilated wavelets are written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)=\lambda_{1}\psi(\lambda_{1}t).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The role of the wavelet transform is to localize the power spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\theta}(t)$
\end_inset

 along short-term windows 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)$
\end_inset

 upon which both time warps 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(t)$
\end_inset

 can be linearized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Wavelet ridge theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following theorem provides an approximate closed form for the wavelet
 transform of a real analytic signal whose amplitude and instantaneous frequency
 have slow variations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem*
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=a(t)\cos\varphi(t)$
\end_inset

.
 The wavelet transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is equal to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\ast\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)=\dfrac{1}{2}a(t)\exp(\mathrm{i}\varphi(t))\times\left(\hat{g}\left(1-\dfrac{\dot{\varphi}(t)}{\lambda_{1}}\right)+\varepsilon(t,\lambda_{1})\right),
\]

\end_inset

where the corrective term satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Vert\varepsilon(t,\lambda_{1})\Vert_{\infty}\leq\left\Vert \dfrac{\dot{a}(t)}{\lambda_{1}a(t)}\right\Vert _{\infty}+\left\Vert \dfrac{\ddot{a}(t)}{\lambda_{1}^{2}a(t)}\right\Vert _{\infty}+\left\Vert \dfrac{\ddot{\varphi}(t)}{\lambda_{1}^{2}}\right\Vert _{\infty}+\sup_{\vert\omega\vert\geq\vert\dot{\varphi}\vert(t)/\lambda_{1}}\vert\hat{g}(\omega)\vert.
\]

\end_inset

The fourth term is negligible if 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\text{\varphi}}(t)\geq\lambda_{1}/Q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

